bug.short_desc: [IAC] Exception when launching a SWT process via the IAC on Linux.

long_desc.thetext:
Exception when launching a SWT process via the IAC on Linux.
When launching a SWT process (e.g. enclosed sample SWT process or the TPTP Manual Test View) - probably any process containing a UI - via the IAC on Linux, the following exception is thrown:
org.eclipse.swt.SWTError: No more handles [gtk_init_check() failed]
Based on https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=115822#c12, this is caused by the process not being able to connect to the X server. The connection to the X server can fail in the following ways: 1. The DISPLAY environment variable is unset 2. The host/port information is wrong 3. The X server is down 4. The socket to the X server is on too high of a file descriptor
I traced this problem to the org.eclipse.hyades.execution/src-local/org/eclipse/tptp/platform/agentcontroller/internal/impl/HyadesMessageProcessorImpl.java#handleLaunchProcess(String,String,Command) method where it is calling /org.eclipse.hyades.execution/src-local/org/eclipse/tptp/platform/agentcontroller/internal/impl/PlatformUtility.java#launchProcess(String,String[],String) which calls java.lang.Runtime#exec(String,String[],File). By passing in the environment array, the launched process does not inherit the environment of the current process (e.g. Eclipse's JVM). As such, the launched process does not have a handle to the local display (despite setting the DISPLAY environment variable) to render the UI. See the enclosed example for more details. Interestingly, setting the DISPLAY environment variable to a remote machine with an accessible X server (e.g. Windows XP running Exceed), the UI is rendered on the remote machine.

This example plugin works the TPTP-4.2.0-200606190100B driver on Linux (IA32).

bug.short_desc: Runtime adapters not loaded correctly

long_desc.thetext:
IAdapterFactory (ies) which plug-in to "org.eclipse.runtime.adapters" are not being loaded unless the plugin in which it is defined is loaded. What I mean by this is that if I define an adapter for A which returns B in a plug-in.xml for a plug-in that has not yet been activated, then that adapter cannot be found until the plug-in is activated.
I will attach a document with two plugins, one of which is not loaded on startup but defines an adapter in the plugin.xml
Set up a run/debug config: Run the example as an Eclipse Application with the "Program to run" as an application: com.sourceprose.eclipse.application. Both com.sourceprose.eclipse and com.sourceprose.eclipse.adapters need to be checked on the Plug-ins list. Modify the configuration to use something other than a default location and check "Clear the configuration area before launching." Clearing the configuration is necessary to make sure that the "com.sourceprose.eclipse.adapters" is not being loaded on application startup.
In the UI, try "Adapter Example"->"Attempt Adapting". You get a null printout in the message box because it cannot adapt an object "ToAdapt" to "Adapted". Then run the "Load Adapter Plugin". This calls "start" for the "com.sourceprose.eclipse.adapters", which will load all of the proper functionality for using the adapter. Try "Attempt Adapting" again and you will get a non-null reference.

Created an attachment (id=45939) Sourcecode for testing adapters
Make sure the config is cleared each time you run, or the plug-in "adapters" will automatically load after the first run of the application.

I had to ask around to figure out the history of this one :-).
The IAdapterManager has 2 methods: getAdapter() that won't cause plugin activation and loadAdapter() that will. You need to use loadAdapter() to cause plugin activation. In your example, you can change the line:
Platform.getAdapterManager().getAdapter(new ToAdapt(), Adapted.class);
into:
Platform.getAdapterManager().loadAdapter(new ToAdapt(), Adapted.class.getName())
Why it works this way is a more interesting question. The IAdapterManager is a fairly generic mechanism and in some cases you don't want an attemp to adapt to cause plugin activation (which can be quite expensive). This also has to do with historical reasons as the mechanism was first made available to be used without XML extensions.
By the way, thanks for providing example! It really saves a lot of time.

bug.short_desc: Clipboard does not copy View.element when the element is derived from the view container

long_desc.thetext:
When the view element is not set, the element is considered to be the view container's element. This is done to optimizes the footprint of serializing a view to XML.
When copying a view whose element is not set, and hence derived from its container's element, the view is copied without an element. Therefore when the view is pasted, its element is incorrect.
When copying such a view at the top level, the derived element needs to be set in the view within the SavingEMFResource.

I'm not sure that this bug is valid. It is up to the client application to determine:
- which views must have explicit references to semantic elements - which views are copyable (for example, compartments generally are not)
The client should ensure that all copyable views have explicit element references. This can be done by implementing the requiresElement(...) method in the AbstractViewFactory subclass. Views that do not are not copyable, because of the consequences cited above.

bug.short_desc: [performance testing] Test measurements results are not realistic

long_desc.thetext:
It appears that the main cause is the move to use jobs pervasively in WTP.
In previous versions, most operations - like opening and closing an editor or validating - were presumed to be mostly synchronous.
In 1.5, some/most validators were updated to run in jobs. Also, opening SSE based editors also spawns a job to create content models for referenced grammars (DOMObserver). These jobs run on 2 seconds delay.
In the validation test case, the measured time was only the time needed to launch the job and not the actual time it took for the job to finish.
When repeatedly opening an editor, we observed an accumulation of jobs all trying to do the same things almost at the same time, because most editors open/close very fast. All this background activity slowed down the workbench and the test results were skewed. We've also seen out of memory situations.
The proposed solution is to wait for all jobs to finish after an action (open editor, validate). This way we will be able to more realistically measure memory consumption and processing time.

bug.short_desc: MethodHelper.findCompatible needs to set accessiblity on directly found methods

long_desc.thetext:
Currently if we don't find a method that matches exactly we go through a process to find the method and then we force it to be accessible. The problem is that if found directly (such as through javaclass.getMethod(name, args)) we don't set the accesibility on these. So what happens is if the class is a static package protected inner class but the method is public the method is found as a public method directly, but it is not set to accessible for it so it fails to execute. If it wasn't an exact match it would of worked. Just because a method is public doesn't mean it is accessible, the class itself may not be accessible.
Check this also for constructors.

bug.short_desc: Bean not instantiated error given if the init string returns a null.

long_desc.thetext:
Currently if the init string returns a null we say that the bean was not instantiated. We should be able to handle a null also. The problem is that we normally use null value for a setting instead of an IJavaInstance for null. But that only works if we have an exact null as the init string in the parsing. But the string could evaluate to null. That should be valid too.
This could be a problem. Need to check what would happen if we have a IJavaInstance but its proxy is null.

bug.short_desc: [MPE] Drop-down list for extra tabs on a multi-page editor does not display correctly.

long_desc.thetext:
For a multi-page editor, when there are too many tabs, the least-used ones are placed in a drop-down list widget. If a tab that is relegated to the drop-down list begins with the "-" character, a divider appears in the drop-down list instead of the name of the tab. The tab's name thus cannot be clicked while in the list.
I assume that this is unexpected behavior resulting from the behavior of the list widget. It's not documented in MultiPageEditorPart.setPageText().
I'm running OS X 10.4.7 with java 1.5.0_06. To recreate the problem, create a multi-page editor plugin. Then alter the auto-generated code to change the names of the pages in the calls to setPageText to something like "-foo". Then run the plugin and resize the Eclipse window to force one of the tabs on to the drop-down list.

Is this still a problem in 3.3?
PW

BTW, I think that the divider behavior is what happens if there's anything unexpected with the name. I forget the exact details, but I saw the divider recently for another mal-formed name that didn't begin with "-".

bug.short_desc: Require API to get resolved APT option values

long_desc.thetext:
AptConfig.getProcessorOptions(IJavaProject) does not resolve variables (like %ROOT% and %PROCESS.DIR%) in the APT option values. Currently, these variables are only resolved during annotation processing. There are cases, where we would need to get the APT option values outside the context of annotation processing and in these cases we get back raw unresolved values.
Even EnvironmentFactory.getEnvironment(compilationUnit, compilationUnit.getJavaProject()).getOptions() does not give back resolved values.
We need some way of getting back these resolved values either through a new API or changing existing ones.

We can do this by pulling the initOptions() and resolveVarPath() methods up from AbstractProcessorEnv to BaseProcessorEnv. Of course, the map returned from BaseProcessorEnv still won't have processing-specific values like "phase", but otherwise it would be useful.
It would also be good to fix AptConfig.getProcessorOptions() so that it returns fully resolved values that are consistent with the value returned from BaseProcessorEnv. To do that, I'll need to do a bit of refactoring (pull the processing out of the Env classes and into some sort of utility class; or perhaps just move it all into AptConfig).

bug.short_desc: Fix getIPAddress() method in ARM agent code

long_desc.thetext: The method org.eclipse.tptp.trace.arm.internal.agent.Agent.getIPAddress() is not always guaranteed to return the "real" ip address of the machine. It sometimes returns 127.0.0.1.

Ashish is the owner of the TPTP ARM Library. Matt owns the UI side of the ARM component. Reassigning.
Fixed in head.
algorithm in patch has issues when multiple network interface cards are present
Created an attachment (id=46598) New patch for getIpAddress() method

The initial patch causes problems with multiple interface cards as Rob mentioned. Some documentation is as follows:
Problem looking up ip address of local machine on Linux ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- When the Agent starts, it needs to look up the IP address of the local machine. The Agent uses a call to InetAddress.getLocalHost() to perform this look up. This should return the 'real' ip address, but on Linux it sometimes returns 127.0.0.1. This is a know bug with the JVM: see here: http://bugs.sun.com/bugdatabase/view_bug.do?bug_id=4665037.
If you encounter this problem, a critical error notifying you of this fact will be output to the log file (as specified by the -Djava.util.logging.FileHandler.pattern=<filename> JVM argument)
This problem will prevent the dynamic discovery feature from working properly. If you are doing everything locally on one machine, then the bug shouldn't affect you.
The work around is to specify your machine's IP address manually. This is done by adding a JVM arg when your application is launched:
IP_ADDRESS=-Dorg.eclipse.tptp.trace.arm.ip=<machine's ip address>
For example, if your ip address is 1.22.333.444, you would add the line
IP_ADDRESS=-Dorg.eclipse.tptp.trace.arm.ip=1.22.333.444
Now fixed in head.
Closed.

bug.short_desc: Separate features storage within one update site

long_desc.thetext:
The update component should allow for seperation of features within an update site.
Consider the following site structure:
site.xml /foo/features/a.feature /foo/plugins/a /bar/features/b.feature /bar/plugins/b
The two features are listed in site.xml as:
<feature url="foo/features/a.feature_1.0.0.jar" id="a.feature" version="1.0.0"> <category name="Test Updates"/> </feature> <feature url="bar/features/b.feature_1.0.0.jar" id="b.feature" version="1.0.0"> <category name="Test Updates"/> </feature>
The features are listed correctly in the update manager but when trying to install the following error occurs:
Unable to retrieve remote reference "file:/D:/test/updates-site/plugins/a_1.0.0.jar".
It seems like the features plugins are searched for relative the site root rather than the location of the feature itself.
It's suggested that the update manager tries to locate plugins using the path "<feature_dir>/../plugins", but maybe there is already other existing solutions for separating features within one update site?

update site has following structure: ->site.xml ->features/ ->plugins/ As you point out plug-ins are searched relative to site.xml. This works fine and there s really no compelling reason to change this and add more separation. BTW you can present your feature separately using categories.

I'd like to separate the physical storage of a features and "their" plugins (ok features references rather than contains plugins) within one update site so categories won't help.
Given that update sites are forced into the following structure: ->site.xml ->features/ ->plugins/
why are features specified with an url? The relative URL foo/features/a.feature_1.0.0.jar seems to resolve but then the update manager always turns to the plugins/ directory when looking for plugins.
Is the only option for separating the physical storage of feature and plugins to use multiple update sites? This will add time to an update check as multiple site.xml needs to be consulted.
archives will do. Check the site.xml schema doc for instance at: http://help.eclipse.org/help32/index.jsp?topic=/org.eclipse.platform.doc.isv/reference/misc/update_sitemap.html

bug.short_desc: C++ Indexer no longer shows progress indication

long_desc.thetext:
In the previous CDT release, the old indexer/parser showed a progress indication. The currently-indexed filename was show, and (more usefully) an indication of % complete was given.
In CDT 3.1 (callisto release), When the indexer is invoked (either automatically or by manually forcing a rebuild from the project's context menu) no % completion is given. Switching to the Progress view, there is an item that simply says "Indexing", with a progress bar at 0%. The progress bar does not move until indexing is complete, at which point it disappears without even briefly showing 100%.
The overall result, from an end-user perspective, is that it looks as if the indexer has "gone wrong", even though the index has been built successfully.
Well, that was on purpose. It turned out that counting how many files I needed to index significantly added to the index time. If we get around to it, we can try it again.

That makes sense (not spending time counting the files) but perhaps the indexer could show some kind of activity - is there a "back and forth" widget available? - so that the user can see the indexer isn't stuck? Or perhaps simply show the name of the currently indexed file, or number of files indexed.
On a QT project, for instance, the first index can take a long time (processing the QT header files) and it's easy to end up assuming the indexer has died/gone into a loop.
The progress bar in the progress view does move when the C/C++ Indexer is running. On windows it goes back and forth and on Linux, I believe it goes left to right over and over again until it's done.

In that case, that's the bug. On fresh installations of Eclipse (from the Callisto source) on both SUSE 10.1 and SUSE 10.0, I don't see any activity on the progress view while the indexer is running. I will try on a Win32 installation of Callisto.

On win32, the progress bar moves left to right (not back and forth) until completion. So this appears to be a platform-specific issue. I will gather some more information but the two platforms tried so far that don't show the progress bar are SUSE 10 (with the distro's default 1.4.2 JVM) and SUSE 10.1 retail version (with the 1.5 JVM that ships with the distro)

I also miss the parsed source file in the progress info. Currently the indexing seems to loop forever for my project. Even after one hour it still continues (an old CDT version used 20 minutes) and there's no way for me to send you a small code example after identifying the problematic file(s).

I have added messages to the indexer that show up when you open the Progress View. In addition to that I have added the trace option 'org.eclipse.cdt.core/debug/indexer' to show the sequence of files indexed on stdout.

Use Bundle-RequiredExecutionEnvironment header in Eclipse 3.0 at your own risk. There are a few reasons this will not work as expected.
1. In Eclipse 3.0 the framework does EE verification at install time. This causes bundles to fail to install if the EE does not match. In Eclipse 3.2 or latter we changed this to happen at resolve time.
2. In Eclipse 3.0 we did not have a concept of EE profiles and therefore did not automatically set the org.osgi.framework.executionenvironment system property automatically to reflect the running EE.
To workaround this issue in 3.0 you have to set the following property in a J2SE 1.4 env.
org.osgi.framework.executionenvironment = OSGi/Minimum-1.0,OSGi/Minimum-1.1,JRE-1.1,J2SE-1.2,J2SE-1.3,J2SE-1.4

Marking as works for me, the suggestion is to not use Bundle-RequiredExecutionEnvironment and instead set javacSource and javacTarget properties.

bug.short_desc: plugin.xml not regenerated

long_desc.thetext:
The sections "org.eclipse.emf.ecore.generated_package" and "org.eclipse.emf.edit.itemProviderAdapterFactories" do not get regenerated when the genmodel is regenerated. This has several consequences:
- when the namespace URI of a package has been changed, care must be taken to change the nsURI (by hand) in the plugin.xml as well.
- when regenerating a EMF project which was created in the time the extension points did not exist yet, they have to be entered by hand in the plugin.xml.
Version: 2.2.0.v200606051102 Build id: 200606051102

(In reply to comment #0)
> > - when the namespace URI of a package has been changed, care must be taken to > change the nsURI (by hand) in the plugin.xml as well. >
The references to the namespace URI in the generated XXXPackage (eNS_URI) and XXXFactoryImpl (in init()) *do* get regenerated, this is not consistent.

We don't have merge support for plugin.xml nor for MANIFEST.MF. You can delete the file to force it to be regenerated. We'll just consider this bugzilla a feature request to support such things, but it's unlikely we'll have time to work on it.
